Ori Movement Feel

responsive but smooth, floaty-but-snappy jumps, strong air control
apex hang time, coyote time + jump buffering, fast-fall, gentle ground stickiness

* Acceleration-based movement (not velocity snaps): fast response, still smooth.
* Different accel/decel on ground vs air: Ori has strong air steering.
* Coyote time + jump buffer: “forgiving” platforming.
* Variable jump height: release early → short hop.
* Apex hang: tiny gravity dip near the top → floaty, controllable.
* Fast-fall: stronger gravity on the way down → snappy landings.
* Ground “stick”: slight downward bias so you don’t hover off slopes/edges.
* Optional abilities hooks: double jump / dash / wall interaction (kept minimal).

Tuning it to feel more like Ori (practical knobs)
These values matter more than code:

1) “Floaty but not sluggish”
	* timeToApex: 0.40–0.48
	* jumpHeight: 3.2–4.2
	* apexGravityMultiplier: 0.45–0.65
	* fallGravityMultiplier: 1.7–2.2
=> If it feels like “space”: increase fallGravityMultiplier and/or decrease apexGravityMultiplier.

2) Ori’s air control is strong
	* airAccel: 60–85
	* airDecel: 45–70
	* maxRunSpeed: 8.5–10.5

3) Forgiveness (Ori is generous)
	* coyoteTime: 0.08–0.12
	* jumpBuffer: 0.10–0.15

4) “Snappy short hops”
	* jumpCutMultiplier: 0.35–0.55
	* Lower = more dramatic short hop.

Other things to consider
1. Corner correction / ledge forgiveness (micro-nudges so you don’t bonk on ledges)
2. Slope handling & snap-to-ground (especially on fast descents)
3. Wall slide / wall jump tuned like Ori
4. Dash with easing + cancel windows
5. Animation-driven “anticipation” (Ori uses a lot of squash/anticipation to sell weight)